{"title_page": "World of Tanks", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent [[WP:Disruptive editing|disruptive editing]]|small=yes}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2019}}\n{{lead too short|date=April 2019}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| title        = World of Tanks\n| image        = World of Tanks.jpg\n| caption      =\n| developer    = [[Wargaming (company)|Wargaming Minsk]]\n| publisher    = Wargaming\n| engine       = \n| composer     = Sergey Khmelevsky\n| released     = {{collapsible list|title=12 August 2010|'''Microsoft Windows'''{{Video game release|RUS|12 August 2010|WW|12 April 2011 (digital)|NA|6 September 2011|EU|2 December 2011}}'''Xbox 360'''|12 February 2014|'''Xbox One'''|28 July 2015|'''PlayStation 4'''|19 January 2016}}\n| genre        = [[Vehicular combat]], [[Massively multiplayer online game|massively multiplayer online]]\n| modes        = [[Multiplayer]]\n| platforms    = [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Xbox One]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[macOS]]\n}}\n\n'''''World of Tanks''''' ('''''WoT''''') is a [[massively multiplayer online game]] developed by Belarusian company [[Wargaming (company)|Wargaming]], featuring mid-20th century (1930s\u20131960s) era [[combat vehicle]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://worldoftanks.com/en/content/guide/general/ |title=General Guide |website=World of Tanks |publisher=[[Wargaming (company)|Wargaming]]}}</ref> It is built upon a [[freemium]] business model where the game is [[free-to-play]], but participants also have the option of paying a fee for use of \"premium\" features. The focus is on [[Player versus player|player vs. player]] gameplay with each player controlling an armored vehicle.\n\n''World of Tanks'' has been ported to multiple gaming consoles. The [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox 360]] and [[Xbox One]] version, called '''''World of Tanks Mercenaries''''', was developed by studio [[Wargaming West]]. ''World of Tanks'' has also expanded to mobile platforms under the title '''''World of Tanks Blitz''''', in addition to a board game titled '''''World of Tanks Rush''''' and a [[collectible card game]] titled '''''World of Tanks: Generals'''''. ''World of Tanks'' was followed by ''[[World of Warplanes]]'' and ''[[World of Warships]]''.\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe player takes control of a single armored vehicle of their choice, and is placed into a battle on a random map. The player has control over the vehicle's movement, firing, and can communicate with allied players through typed or voice chat. A simple random match is won either by destroying all vehicles on the opposing team or capturing the opposing team's base. There are other game modes that change the rules of the battle, but gameplay mechanics remain the same. ''World of Tanks'' contains multiple game mechanics such as camouflage, shell ricochets, and module damage.\n\nThe players in ''World of Tanks'' can choose six primary types of battles: random battles, team-training battles, tank-company battles, team battles, stronghold battles and special battles. Historical Battle and Rampage are former options but have since been taken down for improvement upon its poor reception following its release. Within random battles, players can also participate in platoons, groups of two to three players who are put into the same team. There are also missions to be completed in the game modes for varying amounts of rewards.\n\n=== Vehicles ===\nThe vehicles are modeled to closely resemble their counterparts in real life;<ref>{{cite web |last=Brennan |first=Seraphina |date=18 February 2010 |url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/02/18/world-of-tanks-rolls-onto-the-mmo-battlefield/ |title=World of Tanks rolls onto the MMO battlefield |website=[[Engadget]] ([[Joystiq]]) |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> however, certain parameters have been simplified or modified to fit game mechanics, and better gameplay.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://worldoftanks.com/en/content/guide/general/frequently_asked_questions/ |title=World of Tanks FAQ |website=World of Tanks |publisher=Wargaming |accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> ''World of Tanks'' has five different types of vehicles: [[light tank]]s, [[medium tank]]s, [[heavy tank]]s, [[tank destroyer]]s, and [[self-propelled gun]]s, as well as a few [[main battle tank]]s. The game currently includes over 600 armored vehicles from Britain, China, Czechoslovakia, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Poland, the Soviet Union, Sweden, and the United States. Each nation has at least one line of vehicles starting at tier I to tier X, players progress by playing games in vehicles in that line.\n\nAll vehicles can be customized to a certain degree, either visually or in terms of performance, with the majority of parts (such as tracks, guns, turrets, and engines) being modular parts purchased from the game's tech tree. Various two-tone and three-tone camouflage schemes are available for all tanks as well, including both historically accurate patterns and game-specific, custom variants. [[Camouflage]] is available for temporary use by paying with freely earned in-game credits, or for permanent use by paying with gold purchased in the ''World of Tanks'' store or won in an in-game event.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://worldoftanks.com/en/news/general-news/prepare-yourselves-some-stealthy-tanks/|title=Prepare yourselves for some stealthy tanks|date=1 November 2011|website=World of Tanks|publisher=Wargaming|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> Players can apply national flags, pre-designed slogans, and camouflage (that will slightly increase the chance of remaining undetected).\n\nAll vehicles can mount three pieces of additional equipment, which varies from vehicle to vehicle, and offers various advantages. Some equipment allow the gun to fire faster, some increase the durability of certain parts of the vehicle, and some help keep the vehicle hidden while stationary. Each vehicle can carry three consumables. Examples of these include repair kits, medical kits, and extra rations that boost the tank's crew for the duration of a single battle.\n\n===Clan Wars===\nClan Wars in ''World of Tanks'' has two main components: Strongholds and the Global Map. Each clan can have its own stronghold, if the clan's commander wishes to construct one. Each stronghold begins with one zone and can grow to up to four zones as the clan's membership increases. Many different types of structures exist; however, only one of each can be built. By consuming industrial resources, some structures generate special missions or reserves that can be used to temporarily boost clan members' experience or credits, or enable artillery or airstrikes during a battle for a stronghold. To build structures, industrial resources are required, which can be won by attacking another stronghold or through skirmishes.\n\nThe Global Map is a collection of fronts on a map based on the real world. There are three fronts, one each for tiers 6, 8, and 10. Each front has provinces that generate gold for the clan that currently owns it. A clan may enter the global map by entering a tournament for a specific province, in which they compete against other clans and ultimately the current landowner.\n\n==History==\n{{update section|date=April 2019}}\n[[File:Wikia-Gamescom-2017-Wednesday-014 (35929619014).jpg|thumb|''World of Tanks'' play area at [[gamescom]] 2017|alt=]]\n\nThe developers thought of the concept of ''World of Tanks'' in December 2008.<ref name=\"gamestar.ru\">{{cite web |url=http://gamestar.ru/article/1199.html |title=\u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u0441 Wargaming \u043e World of Tanks |language=Russian |website=[[GameStar]] |date=31 August 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68TGB1pnW?url=http://gamestar.ru/article/1199.html |archivedate=16 June 2012 |url-status=dead |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> The game was officially announced by [[Wargaming (company)|Wargaming]] on 24 April 2009. Developers claim that the game budget was the largest ever in the game industry of the [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://maxigame.by/users/devianse/blog/4478-world-tanks-tankovaya-mmog-ot-wargamingnet |title=World of Tanks \u2014 \u0442\u0430\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f MMOG \u043e\u0442 Wargaming |language=Russian |website=Maxigame |date=25 April 2009 |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlpha testing of the Russian version of the game began September 2009, with only six different vehicles and a single map available. By the beginning of the closed beta test, which started on 30 January 2010, several dozen vehicles and three maps were completed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldoftanks.ru/blog/?p=302|date=25 January 2010|publisher=World of Tanks. Official developers' blog|language=Russian|script-title=ru:\u0418\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0438 \u0430\u043b\u044c\u0444\u0430-\u0442\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430 \"\u041c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u0422\u0430\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432\"|accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> In three months, the number of beta tester requests approached 40,000, and over 400,000 tank battles took place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://game.worldoftanks.ru/news/common/cbt_final_results|title=\u041f\u043e\u0434\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u044b \u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0431\u0435\u0442\u0430-\u0442\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430 World of Tanks|date=18 June 2010|publisher=WorldOfTanks.ru|language=Russian|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621050722/http://game.worldoftanks.ru/news/common/cbt_final_results|archivedate=21 June 2010|url-status=dead|accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> Open beta test of the Russian version started 24 June 2010; at that point, there were seven maps available, along with over 60 Russian and German vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://game.worldoftanks.ru/news/common/wot_open_beta_start|title=\u041d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0441\u044f \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0431\u0435\u0442\u0430-\u0442\u0435\u0441\u0442 \u0438\u0433\u0440\u044b World of Tanks|date=24 June 2010|publisher=WorldOfTanks.ru|language=Russian|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628023342/http://game.worldoftanks.ru/news/common/wot_open_beta_start|archivedate=28 June 2010|url-status=dead|accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> Closed beta test of English version of the game began on 8 July 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://game.worldoftanks.com/news/general_news/closed_beta_begins|title=World of Tanks Closed Beta Begins|date=8 June 2010|publisher=WorldOfTanks.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100711061919/http://game.worldoftanks.com/news/general_news/closed_beta_begins|archivedate=11 July 2010|url-status=dead|accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> The Russian version of the game was officially released on 12 August 2010;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://game.worldoftanks.ru/news/common/online_release|title=12 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u2014 \u0434\u0435\u043d\u044c \u043e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043e\u043d\u043b\u0430\u0439\u043d-\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430|date=13 August 2010|publisher=WorldOfTanks.ru|language=Russian|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816092104/http://game.worldoftanks.ru/news/common/online_release|archivedate=16 August 2010|url-status=dead|accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> however, due to technical difficulties, the game servers went offline on 13 August.\n\nThe [[open beta]] of the English version of the game was launched on 27 January 2011;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://game.worldoftanks.com/news/general_news/open_beta_begins |title=Official Open Beta Begins! World of Tanks Open Beta Launched for Europe and North America |website=World of Tanks |publisher=Wargaming |date=27 January 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130171419/http://game.worldoftanks.com/news/general_news/open_beta_begins |archivedate=30 January 2011 |url-status=dead |accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref> the official release was scheduled for 12 April 2011.<ref name=\"rel-en\">{{cite web |url=http://game.worldoftanks.com/news/general_news/world-tanks-release |title=World of Tanks Release |website=World of Tanks |publisher=Wargaming |date=17 March 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110320183437/http://game.worldoftanks.com/news/general_news/world-tanks-release |archivedate=20 March 2011 |url-status=dead |accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> The ''World of Tanks'' pre-orders were scheduled to be available for the American and European clusters before the game release.<ref>{{cite web |last=Zabek |first=Jim |date=24 March 2011 |url=http://www.armchairgeneral.com/world-of-tanks-special-pre-order-pricing.htm |title=World of Tanks Special Pre-Order Pricing |website=[[Armchair General (magazine)|Armchair General]] |publisher=[[Weider History Group]]}}</ref>\n\n''World of Tanks'' was released online on 12 April 2011 in Europe and North America,<ref name=\"World of Tanks released\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bit-tech.net/news/gaming/pc/world-of-tanks-released/1/|title=World of Tanks released|last=Gorbold|first=James|date=12 April 2011|website=Bit Gamer|publisher=[[Bit-Tech]]|accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> before being released for retail in the latter on 6 September 2011, and in the former on 2 December 2011.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} The game was localised into the Japanese language within the Asia server on 5 September 2013. The Vietnamese server was shut down and merged into the Asia server during 2014.\n\n===Promotion and other media===\n{{expand section|date=April 2019}} <!-- especially Rush and Generals -->\n[[File:Tokyo Game Show 2017 (7).jpg|thumb|upright|Promotion of ''World of Tanks: Roll Out'' at [[Tokyo Game Show]] 2017]]\n\nIn April 2016, Wargaming announced that a comic book based on the ''World of Tanks'' universe is in development. Titled ''World of Tanks: Roll Out'', the five-issue series was written by [[Garth Ennis]] and [[Carlos Ezquerra]], and was set to be published by [[Dark Horse Comics]].<ref>{{cite web |last=McWhertor |first=Michael |date=25 April 2016 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/4/25/11503282/world-of-tank-comic-book-garth-ennis-dark-horse |title=World of Tanks is getting its own comic book, written by Preacher creator |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=26 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Japanese version has collaboration events related to the tank-battle anime series ''[[Girls und Panzer]]''. As of June 2017, Wargaming released two premium tanks, based from the anime series [[Valkyria Chronicles (anime)|''Valkyria Chronicles'']] on the East Asia server. Six voice packs featuring the characters from the anime as well as an expansion pack changing the tanks look have been also released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://girls-und-panzer.jp/giveout.html|title=\u30ac\u30fc\u30eb\u30ba\uff06\u30d1\u30f3\u30c4\u30a1\u30fc(GIRLS und PANZER)\uff5c\u914d\u5e03|website=girls-und-panzer.jp}}</ref> In August 2017, Wargaming and ''World of Tanks'' announced a collaboration with the Swedish metal band [[Sabaton (band)|Sabaton]], shooting a ''World of Tanks'' drive-style video for Sabaton's song \"[[Primo Victoria]]\", and adding a tank named the Primo Victoria to the game, featuring the Sabaton logo, with its crew featuring the visual likeness of Sabaton members, and lead singer [[Joakim Brod\u00e9n]] voicing the captain of the tank.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://worldoftanks.com/en/news/announcements/wargaming-and-sabaton/ |title=Wargaming collaborates with Metal Band Sabaton |website=World of Tanks |publisher=Wargaming |date=8 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://worldoftanks.com/en/news/premium-shop/strv-81-primo-victoria/ |title=Primo Victoria is True Heavy Metal! |website=World of Tanks |publisher=Wargaming |date=24 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=PCGamesN staff |date=17 August 2017 |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/world-of-tanks/world-of-tanks-sabaton-giveaway |title=Win a new Sabaton-voiced tank for World of Tanks, a signed metal album, and a t-shirt! |website=[[PCGamesN]] |publisher=Network N}}</ref>\n\n===''World of Tanks Blitz''===\nIn May 2013, Wargaming announced ''World of Tanks Blitz'', a mobile version of'' World of Tanks'' for tablets and smartphones using [[Windows 10]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Aziz |first=Hamza CTZ |date=4 May 2013 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/wargaming-details-world-of-tanks-blitz-253060.phtml |title=Wargaming details World of Tanks: Blitz |website=[[Destructoid]] |publisher=Enthusiast Gaming}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://wotblitz.com/en/#/ |title=World of Tanks Blitz |website=World of Tanks: Blitz |publisher=Wargaming |accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> The game allows 7v7 battles, as compared to the 15v15 battles on PC. The Closed Beta Test (CBT) started on 19 March, and ended 3 April. ''World of Tanks Blitz'' was released (on iOS only) on May 2014 in European countries like Norway, Sweden, Finland, Denmark, and Iceland, with all other countries, at the time, awaiting launch.<ref name=\"MCV\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mcvuk.com/press-releases/read/world-of-tanks-blitz-release-date-announced/0134080 |title=World of Tanks Blitz Release Date Announced |website=[[MCV (magazine)|MCV]] |publisher=NewBay Media |date=16 June 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714140332/http://www.mcvuk.com/press-releases/read/world-of-tanks-blitz-release-date-announced/0134080 |archivedate=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead |accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> It was released on 27 June 2014 in North America, (again, on iOS only).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/games/world-of-tanks-blitz |title=World of Tanks Blitz |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> Beta testing of the Android version was released in Russia, with ''World of Tanks Blitz'' being released worldwide later on 4 December 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blitzworldoftanks.com/presentation-wot-blitz-for-android/ |title=Presentation WoT Blitz for Android |website=World of Tanks: Blitz |publisher=Wargaming |date=3 December 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231165431/http://blitzworldoftanks.com/presentation-wot-blitz-for-android/ |archivedate=31 December 2014 |url-status=dead |accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe game was released in the [[Windows Store]] on 28 December 2015,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wotblitz.eu/en/news/pc-browser/generalnews/windows10-release-announcement/ |title=World of Tanks Blitz Released on Windows 10 |website=World of Tanks: Blitz |publisher=Wargaming |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220110915/http://wotblitz.eu/en/news/pc-browser/generalnews/windows10-release-announcement/ |archivedate=20 December 2015 |url-status=dead |accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> making it available for PC users running Windows 10. On 9 November 2016, ''World of Tanks Blitz'' was released on Steam.<ref>Jeff Grubb, [https://venturebeat.com/2016/11/09/world-of-tanks-blitz-brings-its-mobile-armored-battles-to-steam/ \"World of Tanks: Blitz brings its mobile armored battles to Steam\"], ''Venture Beat'', 9 November 2016 .Retrieved 1 February 2019.</ref>\n\n===Console versions===\n[[File:Wikia-Gamescom-2016-062 (28971930021).jpg|thumb|''World of Tanks'' at gamescom 2016|alt=]]\n\n'''''World of Tanks: Xbox 360 Edition'''''<ref name=\"worldoftanks1\">{{cite web|url=https://worldoftanks.com/en/news/announcements/wargaming-reveals-world-tanks-xbox-360-edition/|title=E3 2013: Announcing World of Tanks: Xbox 360 Edition|date=10 June 2013|website=World of Tanks|publisher=Wargaming|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> was developed with [[Wargaming West]], formerly Day 1 Studios until purchased early in 2013.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\">{{cite web |last=Hall |first=Charlie |date=10 June 2013 |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3-2013/2013/6/10/4411736/world-of-tanks-xbox-360-edition |title=World of Tanks Xbox 360 Edition: Wargaming's phenomenon comes to the console |website=Polygon |publisher=Vox Media |accessdate=10 June 2013}}</ref> Day 1 was looking for a publisher for their console [[mecha|mech]] game when Wargaming asked the studio about porting World of Tanks.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\" /> Day 1 prototyped the game on the Xbox 360 \"in mere days\".<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\" /> They were given unrestricted access to Wargaming's servers and art.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\" /> The game's client side runs on Wargaming's Despair engine.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\" /> The company aimed to give each tank class 100 hours of unlockable content, or 400 to 500 hours overall.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\" />\n\nThe version is [[free-to-play]] for [[Xbox Live]] Gold subscribers, and includes a 7-day trial for Xbox Live Silver subscribers.<ref name=\"Polygon: free trial\">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/6/13/4425560/world-of-tanks-xbox-360-free-to-play-xbox-live-free-trial|title=Free-to-play World of Tanks on Xbox 360 will offer free trial to non-Gold members|last=Sarkar|first=Samit|date=13 June 2013|website=Polygon|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> Playing the game earns experience for tanks and accessories, and silver for buying tanks and equipment.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\"/> Players can use gold, an [[in-game currency]], to buy premium ''World of Tanks'' accounts, which in turn give players more experience and credits faster.<ref name=\"Polygon: free trial\"/> Players can buy gold with real money in the later patches.<ref name=\"Polygon: free trial\"/> Gold for premium accounts and tanks is the fastest method for progressing through the game.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\"/> The Xbox 360 Edition is not connected with the PC game, with a separate user base and no crossplay.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\"/>\n\nA [[closed beta]] test began in early 2013, and [[E3 2013]] attendees were invited to the beta after the game's announcement.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\"/> The game was working on retail Xbox 360s by mid-May 2013.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\"/> In late May 2013, Wargaming announced that they would be showing its first console game at E3 2013.<ref>{{cite web |last=Farokhmanesh |first=Megan |date=28 May 2013 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/5/28/4373054/wargaming-bringing-its-first-console-game-to-e3-2013 |title=Wargaming bringing its first console game to E3 2013 |website=Polygon |publisher=Vox Media |accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> The game was officially announced during [[Microsoft]]'s E3 2013 press event.<ref name=\"Polygon: free trial\"/> An open beta with 40 American and German tanks was scheduled to begin the weekend after E3 2013.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\"/><ref name=\"Polygon: beta kicks off\">{{cite web |last=Crecente |first=Brian |authorlink=Brian Crecente |date=11 June 2013 |url=https://www.polygon.com/2013/6/11/4417970/world-of-tanks-xbox-360-beta-kicks-off-this-weekend |title=World of Tanks Xbox 360 beta kicks off this weekend |website=Polygon |publisher=Vox Media |accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref> The beta was for [[stress test (hardware)|stress testing]] the servers and multiplayer matchmaking.<ref name=\"Polygon: beta kicks off\"/> Players could not buy gold in the open beta, but Wargaming provided free in-game gold to test the store, though this reset with the official release.<ref name=\"Polygon: free trial\"/> British tanks were also available within the beta.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\"/> About 60 total tanks were expected to be included in the full version.<ref name=\"Polygon: beta kicks off\"/> The open beta was released on 7 August 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://worldoftanksxbox360edition.com/en/news/announcements/world-of-tanks-360-beta-continues/ |title=World of Tanks: Xbox 360 Edition Beta is Available 24/7 |website=World of Tanks |publisher=Wargaming |date=9 August 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101213553/http://worldoftanksxbox360edition.com/en/news/announcements/world-of-tanks-360-beta-continues/ |archivedate=1 November 2013 |url-status=dead |accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> The beta closed on 28 January 2014. All stats on all of the players who participated were reset. The people who participated in the beta got the game first when the full version came out on 12 February 2014.{{fact|date=December 2019}}\n\nOn 18 February 2015, Wargaming announced that they were developing an [[Xbox One]] version of the game. The game was released on 28 July 2015. It supports cross-platform play between Xbox 360 and Xbox One. Players' status and progress can be transferred from the Xbox 360 version to the Xbox One version.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://worldoftanks.com/en/news/announcements/world-of-tanks-xbox-one/|title=World of Tanks is Coming to Xbox One!|date=18 February 2015|website=World of Tanks|publisher=Wargaming|accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> Xbox Live regulations bar Wargaming from offering premium accounts as recurring subscriptions.<ref name=\"Polygon: free trial\"/> Expansion released on 3 June 2014 includes Russian tanks.<ref name=\"Polygon E3 feature\"/> Wargaming West said that if the Xbox 360 version gets a \"meaningful user base\" then they will focus on the Xbox One edition.<ref>{{cite web |last=Wright |first=Jeffrey |date=15 June 2013 |url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/06/15/e3-2013-world-of-tanks-is-blasting-its-way-to-the-360/ |title=E3 2013: World of Tanks is blasting its way to the 360 |website=Engadget (Joystiq) |publisher=Oath Inc. |accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 September 2015 Wargaming announced at the [[Tokyo Game Show]] that ''World of Tanks'' would be coming to the [[PlayStation 4]], developed by Wargaming West, the same studio as the Xbox One and Xbox 360 versions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://forum-console.worldoftanks.com/index.php?/topic/106477-world-of-tanks-is-coming-to-playstation%C2%AE4-faq/ |title=World of Tanks is coming to PlayStation\u00ae4 + FAQ! |website=World of Tanks Xbox & PS4 Version |date=14 September 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161206144001/http://forum-console.worldoftanks.com/index.php?/topic/106477-world-of-tanks-is-coming-to-playstation%C2%AE4-faq/ |archivedate=6 December 2016 |url-status=dead |accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> The PlayStation 4 version was released in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespark.jp/article/2015/09/15/60237.html|title=SCE\u306eTGS\u51fa\u5c55\u60c5\u5831\u304c\u66f4\u65b0 \u2015 PS Vita\u300e\u8056\u5263\u4f1d\u8aac -FF\u5916\u4f1d-\u300f\u3001PS4\u300eWorld of Tanks\u300f\u304c\u63b2\u8f09\u3055\u308c\u308b|date=15 September 2015|website=Gamespark|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\n== Esports ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2019}}\n\n''World of Tanks'' debuted as an [[esports]] game at the [[World Cyber Games 2012]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://worldoftanks.com/en/news/general-news/wcg-2012-wot-debut/|title=WCG 2012, World of Tanks debut|date=21 June 2012|website=World of Tanks|publisher=Wargaming|accessdate=26 November 2018}}</ref> The only official ''World of Tanks'' e-sports tournament is the Wargaming.net League, which takes place on four different regions: CIS, APAC, EU, which have 12 teams each, and NA, which only has 10. The prize pool for the 2016 WGL Grand Finals was US$300,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-wargaming-net-league-grand-finals-inside-world-of-tanks-cyber-olympics/|title=The Wargaming.net League Grand Finals: Inside World Of Tanks' 'Cyber Olympics'|last=Griffin|first=Ben|date=9 April 2014|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|access-date=20 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n=== Critical response ===\n{{Expand section|date=April 2019}}\n{{Video game reviews\n| iOS = true\n| PC = true\n| PS4 = true\n| X360 = true\n| XONE = true\n| na = true\n| Destruct_XONE = 6/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Makedonski |first=Brett |date=3 August 2015 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-world-of-tanks-296821.phtml |title=Review: World of Tanks (XOne) |website=[[Destructoid]] |publisher=Enthusiast Gaming |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n| EGM_XONE = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Patterson |first=Mollie L. |date=19 August 2015 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/world-of-tanks-xbox-one-review/ |title=World of Tanks Xbox One Review |website=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGMNow]] |publisher=EGM Media, LLC |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n| EuroG_PC = 8/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Dean |first=Paul |date=29 November 2011 |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2011-11-29-world-of-tanks-review |title=World of Tanks Review (PC) |website=[[Eurogamer]] |publisher=Gamer Network}}</ref>\n| EuroG_X360 = 7/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Whitehead |first=Dan |date=14 February 2014 |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-02-14-world-of-tanks-xbox-360-edition-review |title=World of Tanks: Xbox 360 Edition review |website=Eurogamer |publisher=Gamer Network |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n| Fam_X360 = 28/40<ref name=\"Fam\">{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |date=10 June 2014 |url=https://gematsu.com/2014/06/famitsu-review-scores-issue-1331 |title=Famitsu review scores: Issue 1331 |website=Gematsu |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n| GamePro_PC = 5/5<ref>{{cite web |last=Rignall |first=Julian |date=28 April 2011 |url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/reviews/219098/world-of-tanks-review/ |title=World of Tanks Review (PC) |website=[[GamePro]] |publisher=GamePro Media |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502015430/http://www.gamepro.com/article/reviews/219098/world-of-tanks-review/ |archivedate=2 May 2011 |url-status=dead |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n| GameRev_PS4 = 4.5/5<ref>{{cite web |last=Haught |first=Jeb |date=9 February 2016 |url=https://www.gamerevolution.com/review/69959-world-of-tanks-