{"title_page": "Runoko Rashidi", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n|image = \n|imagesize = 150px |\n| name        = Runoko Rashidi\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  =  1954\n| birth_place =\n| occupation  = historian, researcher, essayist, author, activist\n}}\n\n'''Runoko Rashidi''' (born 1954) is an American historian, essayist, author and public lecturer based in Los Angeles, California, and Paris, France. He is the author of ''[https://www.amazon.com/Introduction-Study-African-Classical-Civilizations/dp/0907015522 Introduction to the Study of African Classical Civilizations]'' (1993) and the editor of ''Unchained African Voices'', a collection of poetry and prose by [[Death Row]] inmates at California's [[San Quentin Prison|San Quentin maximum-security prison]]. He is a member of the editorial board of ''Africology: The Journal of Pan African Studies'' (www.jpanafrican.org), and he holds an honorary doctorate of divinity from Amen-Ra Theological Seminary (Los Angeles, California). He is also part of an [[Afrocentric]] movement where he supports the work of people like [[Ivan Van Sertima]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rashidi |first1=Runoko |title=Ivan Van Sertima and Runoko Rashidi: The Early Years |url=https://atlantablackstar.com/2014/05/03/ivan-van-sertima-runoko-rashidi-early-years/ |accessdate=11 November 2019 |work=Atlanta Black Star |date=3 May 2014}}</ref> He markets himself as a doctor even though he is not. He has a fake degree from \u201cAmen Ra Theological Seminary\u201d.  The address is a post office box. He sells these degrees to other Afrocentric frauds. He has no education in archeology, anthropology, genetics, linguistics or Egyptology. Despite genetics proving him wrong on his entire beliefs, he sells his services to the gullible. His name is of course not \u201cRunoko Rashidi\u201d, that is his fake Hotep name to give him credibility in the Hotep community.  He has no base in Paris France.\n\n==Scope of work==\nRashidi is a writer and speaker who lectures on topics including [[Ancient Egyptian race controversy|ancient Egypt]], his belief in an African presence in prehistoric America, Africans in antiquity, and the African presence in Asia and other parts of the world.\n\n==Activities==\nHe is the author or editor of 18 books, including ''The African Presence in Early Asia'' (1985, 1988, 1995), with [[Ivan Van Sertima]], ''Black Star: The African Presence in Early Europe'' (2012) and ''African Star over Asia: The Black Presence in the East'' (2013).\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Pan Africanism]]\n*[[Ethnic groups of Africa|African people]]\n*[[Afrocentricity]]\n*[[Ethnology]]\n*[[Martin Bernal]]\n*[[John Henrik Clarke]]\n*[[John G. Jackson (writer)]]\n*[[Critical race theory]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Ivan van Sertima|Van Sertima, Ivan]] (1989). ''Egypt Revisited''. [[Transaction Publishers]]. {{ISBN|0-88738-799-3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cbpm.org/gap.html Articles by Rashidi], The Global African Presence Website (personal website)\n\n{{Pan-Africanism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rashidi, Runoko}}\n[[Category:African-American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Historians of Africa]]\n[[Category:Afrocentrists]]\n[[Category:American Africanists]]\n[[Category:American pan-Africanists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistorians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n|image = \n|imagesize = 150px |\n| name        = Runoko Rashidi\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  =  1954\n| birth_place =\n| occupation  = historian, researcher, essayist, author, activist\n}}\n\n'''Runoko Rashidi''' (born 1954) is an American historian, essayist, author and public lecturer based in Los Angeles, California, and Paris, France. He is the author of ''[https://www.amazon.com/Introduction-Study-African-Classical-Civilizations/dp/0907015522 Introduction to the Study of African Classical Civilizations]'' (1993) and the editor of ''Unchained African Voices'', a collection of poetry and prose by [[Death Row]] inmates at California's [[San Quentin Prison|San Quentin maximum-security prison]]. He is a member of the editorial board of ''Africology: The Journal of Pan African Studies'' (www.jpanafrican.org), and he holds an honorary doctorate of divinity from Amen-Ra Theological Seminary (Los Angeles, California). He is also part of an [[Afrocentric]] movement where he supports the work of people like [[Ivan Van Sertima]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rashidi |first1=Runoko |title=Ivan Van Sertima and Runoko Rashidi: The Early Years |url=https://atlantablackstar.com/2014/05/03/ivan-van-sertima-runoko-rashidi-early-years/ |accessdate=11 November 2019 |work=Atlanta Black Star |date=3 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Scope of work==\nRashidi is a writer and speaker who lectures on topics including [[Ancient Egyptian race controversy|ancient Egypt]], his belief in an African presence in prehistoric America, Africans in antiquity, and the African presence in Asia and other parts of the world.\n\n==Activities==\nHe is the author or editor of 18 books, including ''The African Presence in Early Asia'' (1985, 1988, 1995), with [[Ivan Van Sertima]], ''Black Star: The African Presence in Early Europe'' (2012) and ''African Star over Asia: The Black Presence in the East'' (2013).\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Pan Africanism]]\n*[[Ethnic groups of Africa|African people]]\n*[[Afrocentricity]]\n*[[Ethnology]]\n*[[Martin Bernal]]\n*[[John Henrik Clarke]]\n*[[John G. Jackson (writer)]]\n*[[Critical race theory]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Ivan van Sertima|Van Sertima, Ivan]] (1989). ''Egypt Revisited''. [[Transaction Publishers]]. {{ISBN|0-88738-799-3}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cbpm.org/gap.html Articles by Rashidi], The Global African Presence Website (personal website)\n\n{{Pan-Africanism}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rashidi, Runoko}}\n[[Category:African-American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Historians of Africa]]\n[[Category:Afrocentrists]]\n[[Category:American Africanists]]\n[[Category:American pan-Africanists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Pseudohistorians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "76.66.170.85", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Demographics)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Runoko_Rashidi"}
{"title_page": "Ched Towns", "text_new": "'''Ched Towns''' (16 February 1951 - 20 January 2000) was an vision impaired Australian Paralympic athlete, triathlete and adventurer.\n\n== Personal ==\nTowns was born on 16 February 1951 in [[Penrith, New South Wales]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Schaeffer|first=Stephen|url=|title=Paralympian relished pursuit of adventure - obituary.|date=27 January 2000|work=The Australian|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He was diagnosed with [[retinitis pigmentosa]] at the age of nineteen and by twenty two suffered night blindness. He married Judy and they had two children - Kane and Carlee. His daughter was diagnosed with [[retinitis pigmentosa]], a genetic disease.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ross|first=John|url=https://issuu.com/nepeannews/docs/nepeannews_16february2017/11|title=Cruel diagnosis for Ched Town\u2019s daughter Carlie|date=17 February 2017|work=Nepean News|access-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe worked as a therapist, mediator and motivational speaker. He died on 20 January 2000  at [[Mera Peak]], [[Nepal|Nepal.]]\n\n== Sporting career ==\n<ref name=\":2\" />Towns played rugby league for [[Penrith Panthers]] [[Jersey Flegg Cup|Jersey Fleg Cup]] team until deteriorating eyesight forced him to leave the sport. He then took up triathlon and in 1982 competed in the Nepean Triathlon with wife Judy on the front of a tandem bike. Towns competed in more than 200 triathlons including eight Ironman events. In 1991, he became the Australian triathlete with a physical disability to compete in the [[Ironman World Championship|Hawain Ironman]].<ref name=\":1\" />  He developed a system whereby his wife, Judy, would swim alongside him and then he would ride a tandem bicycle. His children Kane and Carlee would also guide him in triathlons. He ran in the [[City2Surf (Sydney)]] several times. <ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article102046331|title=Sportsmaster Inspires blind athlete|date=27 August 1988|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|access-date=17 April 2020|location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia|page=11 (SECTION D)|via=Trove}}</ref>\n\nHe took up the javelin under the guidance of [[Alf Mitchell]], who won the men's javelin at the [[1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]] in [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth, Western Australia.]] <ref name=\":3\" />At the [[1988 Summer Paralympics|1988 Seoul Paralympics]], he finished fifth in the Men's Javelin B2. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/ched-towns|title=Ched Towns|last=|first=|date=|website=International Paralympic Committee|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Adventures ==\nIn 1993, he was part of the Blind Leading the Blind expedition. The expedition involved Towns and fellow vision impaired Paralympian [[Russell Short]] and able bodied athletes Stuart Andrews and Brian Land. The expedition involved kayaking across the [[Torres Strait]] - [[Cape York Peninsula|Cape York]] to [[Daru]], [[Papua New Guinea]] and walking the [[Kokoda Track|Kokoda Track.]] Towns competed both components of the expedition and the journey is told through the 1995 documentary ''The Blind Leading The Blind'' and the 2004 book ''Blind leading the blind : a journey of vision across the Torres Strait and Kokoda track.''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Andrews|first=Stuart|title=Blind leading the blind : a journey of vision across the Torres Strait and Kokoda track|publisher=New Holland|year=2004|isbn=1741101794|location=French's Forest|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, it was reported that he successfully completed the world's first free-fall for a visually impaired person.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Oliver|first=Paul|date=Sept/Oct 1992|title=From bee stings to triathlons, to skydiving and trekking in Nepal, Ched Townes has shown .. the sky's not the limit.|url=|journal=Triathlon Sports|volume=8|pages=22-24|via=}}</ref> He rode across the [[Simpson Desert]] with his son Chad on a mountain bike for the Paralympic Appeal.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Schaefer|first=Stephen|date=May/June 2000|title=Don't tell me I can't : Ched Towns.|url=|journal=Triathlon Sports|volume=15|pages=10-12|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, with the assistance of two mountaineers he climbed [[Aoraki / Mount Cook]] and [[Fox Glacier]], this was in preparation for climbing the [[Mera Peak]], [[Nepal|Nepal.]] <ref name=\":2\" />On 20 January 2020, he died in climbing Mera Peak.<ref name=\":0\" /> The climb would have equalled the world record for a visuallly impaired person (6471 metres).<ref name=\":2\" /> In April 2000, he had planned to climb a peak of around 7500 metres.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nTowns view of life was \"You want to get to the end of your days and don't want to be sitting there wishing you had done this or that because it is too late then. You have got to do it now while you're fit enough and you're healthy enough\". <ref name=\":2\" /> Towns story was immortalised in the video documentary \u2018''The Moth Loves Doodie''\u2019.\n\n== Recognition ==\n\n* Ched Towns Reserve at [[Glenmore Park, New South Wales|Glenore Park]]\n* 2000 - [[Australian Sports Medal]] for his involvement in a wide variety of sports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/973853|title=Ched Towns|last=|first=|date=|website=It's An Honour website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2016 - [[Triathlon Australia]] Legend<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.triathlon.org.au/About/Celebration_of_Champions/Legend_of_the_Sport_Award/2016_Legends.htm|title=2016 Legends|last=|first=|date=|website=Triathlon Australia website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Towns, Ched}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Australia]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1988 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Visually Impaired category Paralympic competitors]]\n[[Category:Australian male triathletes]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Australian Sports Medal]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Ched Towns''' (16 February 1951 - 20 January 2000) was an vision impaired Australian Paralympic athlete, triathlete and adventurer.\n\n== Personal ==\nTowns was born on 16 February 1951 in [[Penrith, New South Wales]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Schaeffer|first=Stephen|url=|title=Paralympian relished pursuit of adventure - obituary.|date=27 January 2000|work=The Australian|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He was diagnosed with [[retinitis pigmentosa]] at the age of nineteen and by twenty two suffered night blindness. He married Judy and they had two children - Kane and Carlee. His daughter was diagnosed with [[retinitis pigmentosa]], a genetic disease.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ross|first=John|url=https://issuu.com/nepeannews/docs/nepeannews_16february2017/11|title=Cruel diagnosis for Ched Town\u2019s daughter Carlie|date=17 February 2017|work=Nepean News|access-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe worked as a therapist, mediator and motivational speaker. He died on 20 January 2000  at [[Mera Peak]], [[Nepal|Nepal.]]\n\n== Sporting career ==\n<ref name=\":2\" />Towns played rugby league for [[Penrith Panthers]] [[Jersey Flegg Cup|Jersey Fleg Cup]] team until deteriorating eyesight forced him to leave the sport. He then took up triathlon and in 1982 competed in the Nepean Triathlon with wife Judy on the front of a tandem bike. Towns competed in more than 200 triathlons including eight Ironman events. In 1991, he became the Australian triathlete with a physical disability to compete in the [[Ironman World Championship|Hawain Ironman]].<ref name=\":1\" />  He developed a system whereby his wife, Judy, would swim alongside him and then he would ride a tandem bicycle. His children Kane and Carlee would also guide him in triathlons. He ran in the [[City2Surf (Sydney)]] several times. <ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article102046331|title=Sportsmaster Inspires blind athlete|date=27 August 1988|newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]]|access-date=17 April 2020|location=Australian Capital Territory, Australia|page=11 (SECTION D)|via=Trove}}</ref>\n\nHe took up the javelin under the guidance of [[Alf Mitchell]], who won the men's javelin at the [[1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]] in [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth, Western Australia.]] <ref name=\":3\" />At the [[1988 Summer Paralympics|1988 Seoul Paralympics]], he finished fifth in the Men's Javelin B2. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paralympic.org/ched-towns|title=Ched Towns|last=|first=|date=|website=International Paralympic Committee|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Adventures ==\nIn 1993, he was part of the Blind Leading the Blind expedition. The expedition involved Towns and fellow vision impaired Paralympian [[Russell Short]] and able bodied athletes Stuart Andrews and Brian Land. The expedition involved kayaking across the [[Torres Strait]] - [[Cape York Peninsula|Cape York]] to [[Daru]], [[Papua New Guinea]] and walking the [[Kokoda Track|Kokoda Track.]] Towns competed both components of the expedition and the journey is told through the 1995 documentary ''The Blind Leading The Blind'' and the 2004 book ''Blind leading the blind : a journey of vision across the Torres Strait and Kokoda track.''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Andrews|first=Stuart|title=Blind leading the blind : a journey of vision across the Torres Strait and Kokoda track|publisher=New Holland|year=2004|isbn=1741101794|location=French's Forest|pages=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, it was reported that he successfully completed the world's first free-fall for a visually impaired person.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Oliver|first=Paul|date=Sept/Oct 1992|title=From bee stings to triathlons, to skydiving and trekking in Nepal, Ched Townes has shown .. the sky's not the limit.|url=|journal=Triathlon Sports|volume=8|pages=22-24|via=}}</ref> He rode across the [[Simpson Desert]] with his son Chad on a mountain bike for the Paralympic Appeal.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Schaefer|first=Stephen|date=May/June 2000|title=Don't tell me I can't : Ched Towns.|url=|journal=Triathlon Sports|volume=15|pages=10-12|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, with the assistance of two mountaineers he climbed [[Aoraki / Mount Cook]] and [[Fox Glacier]], this was in in preparation for climbing the [[Mera Peak]], [[Nepal|Nepal.]] <ref name=\":2\" />On 20 January 2020, he died in climbing Mera Peak.<ref name=\":0\" /> The climb would have equalled the world record for a visuallly impaired person (6471 metres).<ref name=\":2\" /> In April 2000, he had planned to climb a peak of around 7500 metres.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nTowns view of life was \"You want to get to the end of your days and don't want to be sitting there wishing you had done this or that because it is too late then. You have got to do it now while you're fit enough and you're healthy enough\". <ref name=\":2\" /> Towns story was immortalised in the video documentary \u2018''The Moth Loves Doodie''\u2019.\n\n== Recognition ==\n\n* Ched Towns Reserve at [[Glenmore Park, New South Wales|Glenore Park]]\n* 2000 - [[Australian Sports Medal]] for his involvement in a wide variety of sports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/973853|title=Ched Towns|last=|first=|date=|website=It's An Honour website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2016 - [[Triathlon Australia]] Legend<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.triathlon.org.au/About/Celebration_of_Champions/Legend_of_the_Sport_Award/2016_Legends.htm|title=2016 Legends|last=|first=|date=|website=Triathlon Australia website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Towns, Ched}}\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of Australia]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 1988 Summer Paralympics]]\n[[Category:Visually Impaired category Paralympic competitors]]\n[[Category:Australian male triathletes]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Australian Sports Medal]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ched_Towns"}
{"title_page": "IQOO", "text_new": "{{notability|1=Products|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Chinese smartphone brand}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = iQOO\n| native_name      = \n| logo             = \n| logo_size        = \n| type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry         = [[Smartphone]]s\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|df=yes|2019|3|1}}\n| founder          = \n| location_city    = \n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.iqoo.com/}}\n| area_served      = Worldwide\n| key_people       = \n| products         = [[Smartphones]]\n| num_employees    = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| location_country = [[China]]\n| parent           = [[Vivo (technology company)|Vivo]]\n[[BBK Electronics]]\n}}\n\n'''iQOO''' (pronounced i-koo) is the performance brand of [[Vivo (technology company)|Vivo]] which is wholly-owned by [[BBK Electronics]]. The name abbreviation comes from i Quest On and On. It was officially introduced in 2019.\n\n== References==\n{{Reflist}}{{BBK Electronics}}\n\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Shenzhen]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Chinese companies established in 2019]]\n[[Category:Chinese brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = iQOO\n| native_name      = \n| logo             = \n| logo_size        = \n| type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry         = [[Smartphone]]s\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|df=yes|2019|3|1}}\n| founder          = \n| location_city    = \n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.iqoo.com/}}\n| area_served      = China<br/>India\n| key_people       = \n| products         = [[Smartphones]]\n| num_employees    = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| location_country = [[China]]\n| parent           = [[Vivo (technology company)|Vivo]]\n[[BBK Electronics]]\n}}\n\n'''iQOO''' (pronounced i-koo) is the performance brand of [[Vivo (technology company)|Vivo]] which is wholly-owned by [[BBK Electronics]]. The name abbreviation comes from i Quest On and On. It was officially introduced in 2019.\n\n==Models==\nProducts which also been sold by iQOO and is aimed at the Chinese market when it was expanded to India in 2020.\n\n*The '''iQOO (2019)''' is the first smartphone. It was also the first phone marketed by a newly-launched performance sub-brand in March 2019. Under the hood, the iQOO features the [[List of Qualcomm Snapdragon systems-on-chip|Qualcomm Snapdragon 855]], an eight-core processor which been manufactured in a 7nm process technology. It also features an integrated graphics, the Adreno 640. It runs on [[Android Pie|Android 9 (Pie)]] which is customised with [[Funtouch OS|Funtouch OS 9.0]]. 5G edition is also available.\n*The '''iQOO Neo''' is the second smartphone from the sub-brand. It is powered by the old generation Qualcomm Snapdragon 845 instead of the new Snapdragon 855 which is an eight-core processor. Other versions of the iQOO Neo, one is a 2.84GHz Snapdragon 855 and one is a 2.96GHz Snapdragon 855+.\n*The '''iQOO Pro''' is the third smartphone and is a more powerful version of the iQOO. It comes with a 2.96GHz Snapdragon 855+ processor which first debuted in July 2019 on the [[ROG Phone II|ASUS ROG Phone II]]. It runs on Android 9 \"Pie\" and replaced Funtouch OS with Monster UI.\n*The '''iQOO 3''' launched in 2020, and is the first smartphone to run on [[Android 10]] with iQOO UI. It is powered by a new Snapdragon 865 octa-core processor mated with an Adreno 650 GPU.\n\n== References==\n{{Reflist}}{{BBK Electronics}}\n\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Shenzhen]]\n[[Category:Mobile phone manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Chinese companies established in 2019]]\n[[Category:Chinese brands]]\n", "name_user": "Dl2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "restore to last undamaged version; rv unref, tagvand and nonimprovement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IQOO"}
{"title_page": "The Lego Movie (franchise)", "text_new": "{{Infobox media franchise\n| title = The Lego Movie\n| image = The Lego Movie logo.png\n| imagesize = 250px\n| caption = Logo to the first film.\n| creator = {{unbulleted list|Dan Hageman|Kevin Hageman|[[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord<br />Christopher Miller]]}}\n| origin = ''[[The Lego Movie]]'' (2014)<br />{{based on|[[Lego|Lego Construction Toys]]}}\n| owner = [[The Lego Group|Lego System A/S]]\n| years = 2014\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''''The Lego Movie''''' is a Danish-American [[media franchise]] based on [[Lego]] [[construction toy]]s. It began with the [[The Lego Movie|2014 film of the same name]], which was directed and written by [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller]]. The success of the film led it to receiving two licensed video games, a [[The Lego Movie: 4D \u2013 A New Adventure|theme park film ride attraction]], two spin-off films which were released in 2017, an [[Unikitty!|animated series]] that also came out in the same year as well as a [[The Lego Movie 2: The Second Part|sequel]] in 2019 among other pieces of media. A third spin-off film as well as a sequel to ''The Lego Batman Movie'' are in development. The films in the franchise have received generally positive critical reception, with the exception of ''Ninjago'' which acquired mixed reviews, and has grossed $1 billion at the worldwide box office. It is produced and owned by Warner Bros. Pictures.\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%;\"| Film\n! U.S. <br />release date\n! Director(s)\n! style=\"width:22%;| Screenwriters\n! style=\"width:20%;| Story by\n! Producers\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[The Lego Movie]]''\n| {{Start date|2014|02|07}}\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller]]\n| Dan Hageman, Kevin Hageman, Phil Lord and Christopher Miller\n| [[Dan Lin]] and [[Roy Lee]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]''\n| {{Start date|2017|02|10}}\n| [[Chris McKay]]\n| [[Seth Grahame-Smith]], [[Chris McKenna (writer)|Chris McKenna]], [[Erik Sommers]], Jared Stern and John Whittington\n| Seth Grahame-Smith\n| Dan Lin, Roy Lee, Phil Lord and Christopher Miller\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[The Lego Ninjago Movie]]''\n| {{Start date|2017|09|22}}\n| [[Charlie Bean (filmmaker)|Charlie Bean]], Paul Fisher and Bob Logan\n| Bob Logan, Paul Fisher, William Wheeler, [[Tom Wheeler (writer)|Tom Wheeler]], Jared Stern and John Whittington\n| Hillary Winston, Bob Logan, Paul Fisher, William Wheeler, Tom Wheeler, Dan Hageman and Kevin Hageman\n| Dan Lin, Roy Lee, Chris McKay, Maryann Garger, Phil Lord and Christopher Miller\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[The Lego Movie 2: The Second Part|The Lego Movie 2: <br>The Second Part]]''\n| {{Start date|2019|02|08}}\n| [[Mike Mitchell (director)|Mike Mitchell]] \n| Phil Lord and Christopher Miller\n| Matthew Fogel, Phil Lord and Christopher Miller\n| Dan Lin, Roy Lee, Jinko Gotoh, Phil Lord and Christopher Miller\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | [[The Lego Batman Movie#Future|''Lego Batman Movie'' sequel]]\n| 2022\n| Chris McKay\n| {{N/A|TBA}}\n| {{N/A|TBA}}\n| Dan Lin, Roy Lee, Phil Lord and Christopher Miller\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''The Billion Brick Race''\n| {{N/A|TBA}}\n| [[Jason Segel]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| Jason Segel and [[Drew Pearce]]\n| Dan Lin, Roy Lee, Phil Lord and Christopher Miller\n|}\n\n===''The Lego Movie'' (2014)===\n{{Main|The Lego Movie}}\nThe film was released theatrically on February 7, 2014, through [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]] and [[Village Roadshow Pictures]] to near-unanimous acclaim; critics praised its visual style, humor, voice cast and heartwarming message. It earned more than $257 million in the U.S. and Canada and $210 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of over $469 million. The film won the [[BAFTA Award for Best Animated Film]], the [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Animated Feature]], and the [[Saturn Award for Best Animated Film]]. It was also nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Animated Feature Film]]. The film also received an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"[[Everything Is Awesome]]\".\n\n===''The Lego Batman Movie'' (2017)===\n{{Main|The Lego Batman Movie}}\nIn October 2014, Warner Bros. scheduled the release of ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]'', a spin-off starring [[Batman]], for 2017, moving the release date for ''The Lego Movie 2'' (later titled as ''[[The Lego Movie 2: The Second Part]]'') to 2018.<ref name=Variety10DCComics>{{cite news|last1=Kroll|first1=Justin|title=WB Announces 10 DC Comics Movies, 3 \u2018Harry Potter\u2019 Spinoffs and \u2018Lego\u2019 Sequels|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/warner-bros-dc-justice-league-harry-potter-spinoff-lego-sequel-1201330734/|accessdate=October 15, 2014|work=Variety|date=October 15, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015232002/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/warner-bros-dc-justice-league-harry-potter-spinoff-lego-sequel-1201330734/|url-status=live|archivedate=October 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=124052|title=Warner Bros. DC Comics Movie Slate Fully Revealed!|publisher=ComingSoon.net|accessdate=October 15, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017111735/http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=124052 |url-status=live|archivedate=October 17, 2014}}</ref> [[Will Arnett]] returned to voice Batman, with [[Chris McKay]], who was earlier attached to the sequel, directing the film, the story written by [[Seth Grahame-Smith]], and the film produced by [[Dan Lin]], [[Roy Lee]], [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller]].<ref name=THRBatmanSpinoff>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title='Lego Batman' Spinoff Movie in the Works at Warner Bros. (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/lego-batman-spinoff-movie-works-738631|accessdate=October 15, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 10, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015170920/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/lego-batman-spinoff-movie-works-738631|url-status=live|archivedate=October 15, 2014}}</ref> On April 20, 2015, Warner Bros. scheduled ''The Lego Batman Movie'' for a February 10, 2017 release.<ref name=\"THRR\"/> In July 2015, Arnett's ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]'' co-star [[Michael Cera]] was cast to voice [[Robin (comics)|Robin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/michael-cera-voice-robin-lego-809064|title=Michael Cera to Voice Robin in 'Lego Batman' (Exclusive)|author=Borys Kit|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=July 16, 2015|accessdate=July 16, 2015}}</ref> In August 2015, [[Zach Galifianakis]] entered final negotiations to voice the [[Joker (comics)|Joker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/lego-batman-movie-finds-joker-814851|title='Lego Batman' Movie Finds Its Joker (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Kit|first=Borys|date=August 12, 2015}}</ref> In October 2015, [[Rosario Dawson]] was cast to voice [[Barbara Gordon]], the daughter of police commissioner [[James Gordon (comics)|James Gordon]] who later becomes the crime-fighting heroine [[Batgirl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/lego-batman-rosario-dawson-plat-832508|title='Lego Batman' Finds Its Batgirl (Exclusive)|author=Borys Kit|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=October 16, 2015|accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref> The following month, [[Ralph Fiennes]] was cast as [[Alfred Pennyworth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/ralph-fiennes-lego-batman-finds-836338|title='Lego Batman' Finds Its Alfred with Ralph Fiennes (Exclusive)|author=Borys Kit|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=November 3, 2015|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref> Bruce Wayne's butler. [[Mariah Carey]], although initial reports indicated she was playing Commissioner Gordon,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/11/mariah-carey-the-lego-batman-movie-commissioner-gordon-warner-bros-1201615247/|title=Mariah Carey Playing Commissioner Gordon In 'The Lego Batman Movie'|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Fleming, Jr|first=Mike|date=November 9, 2015}}</ref> was actually cast as [[List of mayors of Gotham City|Mayor McCaskill]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Borys_Kit/status/663790757900226560|title=Borys Kit on Twitter|publisher=|accessdate=December 30, 2016}}</ref> The first trailer for the film was released on March 24, 2016, followed by a second on March 28 the same year. The film was released in the United States on February 10, 2017.\n\nThe score was composed by [[Lorne Balfe]], making it the first film in the franchise to replace [[Mark Mothersbaugh]].<ref name=\"lorne-balfe-fmr\">{{cite news|title=Lorne Balfe to Score \u2018The Lego Batman Movie\u2019|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2016/06/09/lorne-balfe-to-score-the-lego-batman-movie/|accessdate=June 9, 2016|work=Film Music Reporter|publisher=Film Music Reporter|date=June 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===''The Lego Ninjago Movie'' (2017)===\n{{Main|The Lego Ninjago Movie}}\nBrothers Dan and Kevin Hageman, who wrote ''[[Lego Ninjago: Masters of Spinjitzu|Ninjago: Masters of Spinjitzu]]'' and co-wrote the story of ''[[The Lego Movie]]'', co-wrote the film adaptation of ''[[Lego Ninjago]]'', which features a new take that diverges from the TV series. [[Charlie Bean (animator)|Charlie Bean]], who produced Disney's ''[[Tron: Uprising]]'', directed the film, produced by ''The Lego Movie'' team of [[Dan Lin]], [[Roy Lee]], [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller]].<sup>[31]</sup> The spin-off movie was scheduled to be released on September 23, 2016.<sup>[32]</sup> On April 20, 2015, the film was delayed until September 22, 2017 as ''[[Storks (film)|Storks]]'' took over the original release date of the movie.<sup>[12]</sup> In June 2016, the cast was announced to include [[Jackie Chan]], [[Dave Franco]], [[Michael Pe\u00f1a]], [[Abbi Jacobson]], [[Kumail Nanjiani]], [[Zach Woods]] and [[Fred Armisen]] respectively. It is the second-to-last film to be distributed by Warner Bros. Pictures.\n\n===''The Lego Movie 2: The Second Part'' (2019)===\n{{Main|The Lego Movie 2: The Second Part}}\nBefore the critical acclaim and blockbuster success of ''[[The Lego Movie]]'', talks for a sequel were already in motion. On February 3, 2014, Jared Stern and Michelle Morgan were tasked to write a screenplay.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thewrap.com/warner-bros-writer-jared-stern-already-working-sequel-lego-movie-exclusive/|title=Warner Bros. Already Working on Sequel to \u2018The Lego Movie\u2019 (Exclusive)|publisher=The Wrap|first=Lucas|last=Shaw|date=February 3, 2014|accessdate=February 23, 2014|archivedate=March 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305084230/http://www.thewrap.com/warner-bros-writer-jared-stern-already-working-sequel-lego-movie-exclusive/|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 21, 2014, the studio scheduled the sequel for a May 26, 2017, release.<ref name=comingsoon1>{{cite news|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=115163|title=The LEGO Movie Sequel is Officially Set for May 26, 2017!|publisher=ComingSoon.net|accessdate=February 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225013931/http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=115163|archivedate=February 25, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 12, 2014, ''[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]'' reported that the first film's animation co-director [[Chris McKay]] would direct the sequel with [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller]] as producers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/03/warner-bros-builds-lego-sequel-with-chris-mckay-directing/|title=Warner Bros Builds LEGO Sequel With Chris McKay Directing|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 12, 2014|accessdate=March 11, 2014|archivedate=March 13, 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313153825/http://www.deadline.com/2014/03/warner-bros-builds-lego-sequel-with-chris-mckay-directing/}}</ref> [[Warner Bros.]] did not invite co-producer of the first film, [[Village Roadshow Pictures]], to return as a participant in the sequel, due to Warner Bros. having now more confidence in the film and trying to keep as much profit as possible for itself.<ref name=THRCutOut>{{cite news|date=March 26, 2014|accessdate=April 19, 2014|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lego-movie-2-village-roadshow-691087|title='Lego Movie' Backer Village Roadshow Cut Out of Sequel (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609001113/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lego-movie-2-village-roadshow-691087|archivedate=June 9, 2014}}</ref> On April 10, 2014, McKay expressed that he would like to introduce more women in the sequel than men.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/womenandhollywood/lego-movie-sequel-director-regretful-original-film-fails-the-bechdel-test-wants-to-do-better|title= Lego Movie Sequel Director Regretful Original Film Fails &#124; Women and Hollywood|publisher=Indiewire|date=April 11, 2014|accessdate=August 15, 2014|archivedate=April 13, 2014|url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413183004/http://blogs.indiewire.com/womenandhollywood/lego-movie-sequel-director-regretful-original-film-fails-the-bechdel-test-wants-to-do-better}}</ref> On July 28, 2014, it was reported that on the internet, [[Chris Pratt]] expressed interest in reprising his role as Emmet for the sequel.<ref>{{cite web|date=July 28, 2014|accessdate=August 15, 2014|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a586776/chris-pratt-id-love-to-return-for-lego-movie-sequel.html#~oMXDObAe2SbZWA|title=Chris Pratt: 'I'd love to return for Lego Movie sequel'|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140816225841/http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/news/a586776/chris-pratt-id-love-to-return-for-lego-movie-sequel.html#~oMXDObAe2SbZWA|archivedate=August 16, 2014}}</ref> It was also reported that [[Will Arnett]] might return as Batman, but had not decided yet.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nIn October 2014, Warner Bros. scheduled ''The Lego Batman Movie'' for 2017, and ''The Lego Movie 2'' for 2018.<ref name=Variety10DCComics /> By October 25, 2014, Lord and Miller had signed on to write ''The Lego Movie 2''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fleming|first1=Mike, Jr.|title=\u2018Lego Movie\u2019 Sequel Gets Phil Lord, Chris Miller Script Commitment|url=https://deadline.com/2014/10/lego-movie-sequel-phil-lord-chris-miller-writing-860896/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=October 26, 2014|date=October 25, 2014}}</ref> The writers have implied that the sequel will take place four years after the events of ''The Lego Movie''.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=43091| title = Phil Lord And Chris Miller On The Upcoming Lego Movies | first = Ali |last=Plumb | work = Empire | date = January 7, 2015 | accessdate = March 22, 2015}}</ref> In February 2015, Warner Bros. announced that the title of the sequel had been changed to ''The Lego Movie Sequel'', and that [[Rob Schrab]], co-writer of ''[[Monster House (film)|Monster House]]'' replaced McKay as director since McKay went to direct ''The Lego Batman Movie''.<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.warnerbros.co.uk/whats-hot/articles/2015/february/the-lego-movie-sequel--new-director-revealed | title= The LEGO\u00ae Movie Sequel - New director revealed | date=February 25, 2015| publisher=Warner Bros.|accessdate=March 22, 2015|archive-date= March 22, 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150322170959/https://www.warnerbros.co.uk/whats-hot/articles/2015/february/the-lego-movie-sequel--new-director-revealed|url-status=live}}</ref> According to an interview at the [[Santa Barbara International Film Festival]], the sequel will focus on Emmet and his sister, taking place in \"weird, dystopian version of Bricksburg.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Brew|first1=Simon|title=The LEGO Movie 2: early details revealed|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/movies/the-lego-movie/33962/the-lego-movie-2-early-details-revealed|publisher=Den of Geek!|accessdate=March 6, 2017|date=February 5, 2015}}</ref> On April 20, 2015, Warner Bros. scheduled ''The Lego Movie Sequel'' for a May 18, 2018 release date.<ref name=\"THRR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/lego-batman-movie-gets-release-790232|title='The Lego Batman Movie' Gets Release Date|author=Borys Kit|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=([[Prometheus Global Media]])|date=April 20, 2015|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref> On June 17, 2016, the film's release was delayed until February 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title='Lego Movie 2' Pushed Nine Months to Winter 2019|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lego-movie-2-pushed-nine-904213|accessdate=March 6, 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> By July 2016, [[Raphael Bob-Waksberg]] had been hired to do rewrites of the script.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/lego-movie-sequel-screenplay-rewrite-raphael-bob-waksberg-1201810241/|title=\u2018Lego Movie Sequel\u2019 Getting Rewrite From \u2018BoJack Horseman\u2019 Creator (EXCLUSIVE)|first=Justin|last=Kroll|work=Variety|date=July 7, 2016|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> By February 2017, Schrab had been replaced by [[Mike Mitchell (director)|Mike Mitchell]], reportedly due to \"creative differences\".<ref name=THREnlistsMitchell>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|last2=Galuppo|first2=Mia|title='Lego Movie' Sequel Enlists 'Trolls' Director Mike Mitchell (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/lego-movie-sequel-enlists-trolls-director-mike-mitchell-971657|accessdate=February 3, 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> On September 6, 2017, it was announced that production of ''The Lego Movie Sequel'' would begin in [[Canada]] on October 2, 2017.<ref>http://moviehole.net/2017123123lego-movie-2-begins-production-in-october</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brickfanatics.com/production-about-to-begin-on-the-lego-movie-sequel/|title=Production about to begin on The LEGO Movie Sequel|first=|last=Graham|date=8 September 2017|publisher=}}</ref> It was also announced that Lord and Miller have returned to re-rewrite the script to tackle with gender issues on how a girl plays vs. how a boy plays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/lego-movie-2-lord-miller-writers-themes/|title=Lord & Miller Rewriting LEGO Movie 2|date=14 September 2017|website=ScreenRant}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, 2018, it was confirmed that [[Tiffany Haddish]] was cast in the film as a new lead character while returning actors would be Pratt as regular guy turned Master Builder Emmet Brickowski, [[Elizabeth Banks]] as Wyldstyle, Arnett as Batman, [[Channing Tatum]] as Superman and [[Jonah Hill]] as Green Lantern.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/tiffany-haddish-the-lego-movie-sequel-1202734779/|title=Tiffany Haddish to Star in \u2018The Lego Movie\u2019 Sequel|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=2018-03-23|work=Variety|access-date=2018-03-23|language=en-US}}</ref>\nOn May 21, 2018, Warner Bros. officially renamed the film ''The Lego Movie 2: The Second Part'' along with releasing the first teaser poster.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/the-lego-movie-2-title-logo/|title=\u2018The LEGO Movie 2\u2019: Full Title and Logo Revealed|first=Matt|last=Goldberg|date=21 May 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/947181-prepare-for-second-part-in-new-lego-movie-2-logo|title=Prepare for the Second Part in the New LEGO Movie 2 Logo|date=21 May 2018|website=ComingSoon.net}}</ref>\n\n====Untitled ''Lego Batman Movie'' sequel (2022)====\nIn December 2018, Chris McKay confirmed that a sequel was in development and that he would return to direct the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2018/12/05/lego-batman-movie-2-sequel-lego-movie-chris-mckay/|title='LEGO Batman Movie 2' in the Works|website=ComicBook.com|last1=Anderson|first1=Jenna|date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> However, the fate of this film is uncertain due Warner Bros. losing the Lego film rights to Universal. \n\n====''The Billion Brick Race''====\nIn March 2015, Warner Bros. announced that a third ''[[The Lego Movie|Lego Movie]]'' spin-off, titled ''The Billion Brick Race'', was in development. By July 2016, [[Jason Segel]] and [[Drew Pearce]] signed onto the project as co-directors and co-writers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/new-lego-spinoff-movie-works-784244|date=March 25, 2015|accessdate=July 14, 2016|first1=Tatiana|last1=Siegel|first2=Borys|last2=Kit|title=New 'Lego' Spinoff Movie in the Works From Jason Segel, 'Iron Man 3' Writer (Exclusive)|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Film Releases|url=http://www.varietyinsight.com/print_featurefilm_releases.php|accessdate=March 5, 2017|work=Variety}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wolfe|first1=Jennifer|title=Warner Bros. Resets Release Dates for Next Three \u2018LEGO\u2019 Features|url=http://www.awn.com/news/warner-bros-resets-release-dates-next-three-lego-features|publisher=Animation World Network|accessdate=March 5, 2017|date=April 21, 2015}}</ref> In August 2017, it was announced that [[Jorge Gutierrez (animator)|Jorge R. Gutierrez]] was hired to replace Pearce as co-director. At that time, the film was scheduled to be released on May 24, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/lego-movie-spinoff-billion-brick-race-director/|title=LEGO Spinoff Billion Brick Race Finds New Director|date=2 August 2017|website=ScreenRant}}</ref> By February 2018, Gutierrez had left the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/news/jorge-gutierrez-departs-director-lego-movie-spinoff|title=Jorge Gutierrez Departs as Director of 'LEGO Movie' Spinoff|website=Animation World Network|last1=McLean|first1=Tom|date=February 8, 2018|accessdate=February 9, 2018}}</ref> \n\nIn July 2018, the film's plot was announced by Pearce to be a Lego racing movie, inspired by pre-existing race car films, including ''[[The Cannonball Run]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/lego-movie-billion-brick-race-cannonball-run/|title=LEGO Movie Spinoff Billion Brick Race Inspired by Cannonball Run|date=16 July 2018|website=ScreenRant}}</ref> Dan Lin, Roy Lee, Phil Lord and Christopher Miller return as producers. \n\nThere\u2019s a possibility that it might be distributed by Universal Pictures, but it is uncertain whether it is cancelled or still in production at Universal Pictures.\n\n===Future===\nIn December 2019, [[Universal Pictures]] entered early negotiations to distribute upcoming feature film properties based on the Lego toys. Although the original ''Lego Movie'' characters are still owned by Warner Bros. Pictures, Universal Pictures will serve as distributor of future release and will develop additional ''Lego'' films, and will be working on their own LEGO film series. The future of the already in-development movies, is believed to remain the same.<ref>{{cite web |date= 19 December 2019 |author= Matt Donnelly |title= Universal in Talks With Lego Group to Develop New Films Based on Toys (EXCLUSIVE) |url= https://variety.com/2019/film/news/universal-pictures-in-talks-for-lego-film-deal-1203449172/ |website=Variety }}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n{{Main|Unikitty!}}\n\nIn May 2017, [[Warner Bros.]] and [[The Lego Group|Lego]] announced that [[List of The Lego Movie characters#Princess Unikitty|Unikitty]], a character from ''[[The Lego Movie]]'', would get a spin-off animated television series on [[Cartoon Network]]. For the show, she is voiced by [[Tara Strong]]. The premiere date was January 1, 2018 and the show's executive producers are [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Phil Lord]], [[Phil Lord and Christopher Miller|Christopher Miller]], [[Dan Lin]], [[Roy Lee]], Jill Wilfert and [[Sam Register]]. [[Ed Skudder]] (creator of ''[[Dick Figures]]'' and co-creator of ''Dogsnack'') and Lynn Wang (co-creator of ''Dogsnack'') are signed as producers while [[Aaron Horvath]] serves as supervising producer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unikitty TV series coming to Cartoon Network|url=http://brickset.com/article/27328/unikitty-tv-series-coming-to-cartoon-network|publisher=Brickset|accessdate=March 30, 2017|date=March 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Nordyke|first1=Kimberly|title='Lego Movie's' Unikitty Gets Animated Series at Cartoon Network|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/lego-movies-unikitty-gets-animated-series-at-cartoon-network-1001877|accessdate=May 1, 2017|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ccW59pHI7H0&t=29s|title=Comic Con San Diego 2017 - Unikitty - (Producers)|first=|last=GeekRock TV|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> The series aired a Halloween special/sneak peek titled \"Spoooooky Game\" on October 27, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CNschedules/status/921177045937291264|title=Unikitty is premiering much earlier than expected, with a sneak peek/Halloween episode next Friday at 6:15pm!|first=CN Schedule|last=Archive|date=19 October 2017|publisher=}}</ref> The series aired a second sneak peek \"Sparkle Matter Matters\" on November 17, 2017 and a third and final sneak peek/Christmas special titled \"No Day Like Snow Day\" aired December 1, 2017.\n\n==Short films==\nShort films based on the films were created to promote the franchise. Some were released individually, specifically on the internet and/or theatrically. Others were included on the home media releases of the films.\n\n===''Chinese New Year'' (2014)===\n''Chinese New Year'' is a short that was released on YouTube in January 2014.<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qnC2YmGWnys|title=The LEGO Movie - Chinese New Year [HD]|date=January 31, 2014|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> In the short, Emmet wishes the viewer a happy [[Chinese New Year]] and tries to remember what \"Year\" it is on the Chinese calendar. He also tries to communicate with a horse in costume.\n\n===''Puppy Bowl Coin Toss'' (2014)===\n''Puppy Bowl Coin Toss'' is a short released in February 2014, featuring Emmet tossing the coin to begin [[Puppy Bowl|Puppy Bowl X]].<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0mey8dY-eDY|title=The LEGO Movie - Puppy Bowl Coin Toss [HD]|date=February 2, 2014|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===''Enter the Ninjago'' (2014)===\n{{Main|Enter the Ninjago}}\n''Enter the Ninjago'' is a short film included on the home media release of ''The Lego Movie''.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} The president of Hollywood sits down with Emmet and changes up the plot of ''The Lego Movie'' to prominently feature [[ninja]]s for marketing purposes.\n\n===''The Emmet Awards Show!'' (2014)===\n''The Emmet Awards Show!'' is a short that was released on YouTube in September 2014.<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eQwDUzqIq5I|title=The Emmet Awards Show! - The LEGO Movie|date=September 10, 2014|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> In the short, Emmet hosts an awards show to announce the winners of real-life contests which Lego held earlier in the year, but there are some technical difficulties.\n\n===''Behind the Bricks'' (2014 \u2013 2017)===\n''Behind the Bricks'' is a series of fictional \"behind-the-scenes\" videos in which the characters of the movies discuss the (fictional) making of their movies. As of February 2019, there are three videos in the series - one each for ''The Lego Movie'',<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cH4tMSd3QJY|title=The LEGO Movie - \"Behind the Bricks\" Featurette|date=January 24, 2014|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> ''The Lego Batman Movie'',<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fGDW5kRKsYo|title=The LEGO Batman Movie - \"Behind the Bricks\" Featurette|date=January 26, 2017|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> and ''The Lego Ninjago Movie''.<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sbdPjhyLZ7k|title=The LEGO Ninjago Movie {{!}} Meet the Cast {{!}} Behind the Bricks {{!}} Cartoon Network|date=September 16, 2017|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===''Outtakes'' (2014 \u2013 2017)===\n''Outtakes'' is a series of fictional \"[[Blooper|outtakes]]\", presented as though they occurred in-universe while the characters were making their movies. As of February 2019, there are three videos in the series - one each for ''The Lego Movie'',<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W5YsU826l20|title=The LEGO Movie - Outtakes [HD]|date=February 14, 2014|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> ''The Lego Batman Movie'', and ''The Lego Ninjago Movie''.\n\n===''The Master'' (2016)===\n''The Master'' is a 2016 computer animated short film written and directed by Jon Saunders, co-written by Ross Evans, Carey Yost and Remington D. Donovan and produced by Ryan Halprin. The short film was released on September 23, 2016, with [[Warner Bros. Animation|Warner Animation Group]]'s [[Storks (film)|''Storks'']], as well as early showings of ''The Lego Batman Movie'' in the United Kingdom. It stars [[Jackie Chan]] as Master Wu, [[Abbi Jacobson]] as The Chicken, and [[Justin Theroux]] as Narrator.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/behind-screen/new-lego-short-master-debut-922834|title=New Lego Short 'The Master' To Debut Before 'Storks'|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> The short follows Wu and an annoying chicken. This is the first Lego short film to be released in theaters, and is also the first theatrical short film from ''The Lego Movie'' franchise.\n\n===''Batmersive VR Experience'' (2017)===\n''Batmersive VR Experience'' is a virtual reality short film, released on the internet in April 2017. [[Batman]] takes the viewer on a tour of the [[Batcave]] and other places of [[Gotham City]] to show the ways of being his sidekick.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Childress|first1=Ahmad|title=The Lego Batman Movie VR Experience|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2017/04/17/the-lego-batman-movie-vr-experience|publisher=IGN|accessdate=June 24, 2017|date=April 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===''Gotham Cribs'' (2017)===\n''Gotham Cribs'' is a short that was released on YouTube in February 2017.<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WkOwqr9N5pE|title=The LEGO Batman Movie - Gotham Cribs|date=February 2, 2017|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> In the short, Batman takes the viewer on a tour of Bruce Wayne's mansion and tries not to reveal that he is in fact Bruce Wayne.\n\n===''Dark Hoser'' (2017)===\n''Dark Hoser'' is a short film included on the home media release of ''The Lego Batman Movie''.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} Batman attends a tryout to apply to be a member of the [[Justice League of America]], but only finds out he might be Canadian.\n\n===''Batman is Just Not That Into You'' (2017)===\n''Batman is Just Not That Into You'' is a short film included on the home media release of ''The Lego Batman Movie''.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} [[Harley Quinn]] hosts a talk show and helps [[Joker (comics)|The Joker]] break up with Batman.\n\n===''Cooking with Alfred'' (2017)===\n''Cooking with Alfred'' is a short film included on the home media release of ''The Lego Batman Movie''.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} [[Alfred Pennyworth|Alfred]] hosts a cooking show with Batman and [[Robin (comics)|Robin]] as his guest stars.\n\n===''Movie Sound Effects: How Do They Do That?'' (2017)===\n''Movie Sound Effects: How Do They Do That?'' is a short film included on the home media release of ''The Lego Batman Movie''.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} [[Bane (comics)|Bane]], [[The Riddler]], [[Poison Ivy (comics)|Poison Ivy]] and [[Catwoman]] are brought into a sound booth to help record sound effects for ''The Lego Batman Movie''.\n\n===''SDCC Greeting'' (2017)===\n''SDCC Greeting'' is a short released in July 2017,<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P-Zb7D1w0Hs|title=The LEGO NINJAGO Movie - SDCC Greeting|date=July 19, 2017|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> featuring Lord Garmadon and Lloyd announcing their upcoming trip to [[San Diego Comic-Con International]].\n\n===''Shark E. Shark in \"Which Way To The Ocean?\"'' (2017)===\n''Shark E. Shark in \"Which Way To The Ocean?\"'' is a short film included on the home media release of ''The Lego Ninjago Movie''.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} The short follows a baby shark who tries make its way back the ocean after getting shot out of Garmadon's Shark cannon. The short is animated in the style of the artwork seen in Lego instruction booklets.\n\n===''Zane's Stand Up Promo'' (2017)===\n''Zane's Stand Up Promo'' is a short film included on the home media release of ''The Lego Ninjago Movie''.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} The short itself is a humorous promo for a [[Stand-up comedy]] DVD starring Zane.\n\n===''Turkish Airlines: Safety Videos with The LEGO Movie Characters'' (2018 \u2013 2019)===\nOn August 1, 2018, a short film marketed as a promotional tie-in and teaser to ''The Lego Movie 2: The Second Part'' unofficially titled ''Turkish Airlines: Safety Video with The LEGO Movie Characters'' was released. It is an [[airline safety video]] featuring characters from ''The Lego Movie'' franchise and was developed as part of a partnership between [[Warner Bros.]] and [[Turkish Airlines]]. It is presented by Emmet and Lucy while featuring cameo appearances from multiple characters all across the different areas of the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/heres-last-airline-safety-video-ever-need-courtesy-lego-movie-173323327.html|title=Here's the last airline safety video we'll ever need, courtesy of 'The Lego Movie'|website=www.yahoo.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://airwaysmag.com/airlines/turkish-airlines-unveils-safety-video-in-partnership-with-warner-bros-and-the-lego-movie/|title=Turkish Airlines Unveils Safety Video in Partnership with Warner Bros. And The LEGO Movie|date=2 August 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/batman-lego-movie-characters-turkish-airlines-safety-video|title=Batman and other LEGO Movie characters assemble for Turkish Airlines safety video|first=Josh|last=Weiss|date=1 August 2018|website=SYFY WIRE}}</ref> On February 7, 2019, another one was released with sequel characters.<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MqbFPn_FwaE|title=Safety Video with The LEGO Movie 2 Characters - Turkish Airlines|date=February 7, 2019|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===''Emmet's Holiday Party'' (2018)===\nOn December 10, 2018, Warner Bros. released a Christmas-styled promotion for ''The Lego Movie 2: The Second Part'', titled ''Emmet's Holiday Party''.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-12-13|title=Christmas Comes To Apocalypseburg In A Lego Movie 2 Short Film|url=https://www.empireonline.com/people/chris-pratt/christmas-comes-apocalypseburg-lego-movie-2-short-film/|date=10 December 2018|website=Empire}}</ref> It will be featured on the DVD release of the film. In Apocalypseburg (the name for Bricksburg in its post-apocalyptic condition), Emmet uses his Master Builder skills to throw a big Christmas Party to make everything awesome again. The short was eventually included as a bonus feature on ''[[The Lego Movie 2: The Second Part]]'''s home media release.\n\n===''Saving Bricksburg'' (2019)===\n''Saving Bricksburg'' is a series of short films released on [[Lego]]'s official YouTube channel from January 5, 2019 to February 2, 2019. These films include ''Batman Saves Bricksburg,''<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6cb3EL9jgus|title=Batman Saves Bricksburg - THE LEGO MOVIE 2 - The LEGO Movie ReTelling|date=January 5, 2019|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> ''Lucy Saves Bricksburg,''<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X3Ukfd4411g|title=Lucy Saves Bricksburg - THE LEGO MOVIE 2 - The LEGO Movie ReTelling|date=January 12, 2019|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> ''Benny Saves Bricksburg,''<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fMBjmrJ4LHs|title=Benny Saves Bricksburg - THE LEGO MOVIE 2 - The LEGO Movie ReTeling|date=January 19, 2019|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> ''Unikitty Saves Bricksburg,''<ref>{{cite AV Media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ga1JJc0ToVE|title=Unikitty Saves Bricksburg - THE LEGO MOVIE 2 - The LEGO Movie ReTelling|date=January 26, 2019|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> and ''Emmet Saves Bricksburg.''<ref>{{cite AV Media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rsorIWt5d7c|title=Emmet Saves Bricksburg - THE LEGO MOVIE 2 - The LEGO Movie ReTelling|date=February 2, 2019|via=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> Narrated by children, each film depicts a short retelling of ''The Lego Movie'', focusing on each character's perspective of the film.\n\n===''\"Everything is Awesome\" Dance Together Music Video'' (2019)===\nOn January 8, 2019, one month before the release of ''The Lego Movie 2: The Second Part'', the Lego channel released another short film, a music video, ''\"Everything is Awesome\" Dance Together Music Video''. Using the [[Everything Is Awesome!!!|titular song]], the video depicts characters from the original film and sequel dancing to the song.<ref>{{cite AV media | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9UJ1syXaNoQ | title = \"Everything Is Awesome\" Dance Together Music Video - THE LEGO MOVIE 2 - Music Video | work = LEGO | publisher = [[YouTube]]}}</ref> A 360\u00b0 version was released one week and a day later (January 16).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ftW0SDZXsv4|title=\"Everything Is Awesome\" Dance Together 360 - THE LEGO MOVIE 2 - 360 Video|date=January 16, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===''The LEGO Chevy Silverado - Getaway'' (2019)===\nOn February 7, 2019, Lego and [[Chevrolet]] teamed up to create a commercial for their newest [[Chevrolet Silverado]] car model.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NyTfdPe3YSk|title=The LEGO\u00ae Chevy Silverado \u2013 Getaway {{!}} Chevrolet|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> Due to copyright infringements, the video has been removed and reuploaded to and from YouTube several times.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} The commercial depicts Emmet and Lucy escaping from Sweet Mayhem's ship initially in their own car, but it is destroyed, so they are introduced to a Lego architect of the new Chevy. During the ride, Emmet explains the vehicle's features and a voice from somewhere makes Lucy suspicious. The commercial ends with Emmet breaking the fourth wall by telling Lucy they are in a commercial, and Lucy expresses her opinion of not liking commercials.\n\n===''\"Awesome\" Late Payment Forgiveness - Discover'' (2019)===\nAround the same time as the Chevrolet commercial, [[Discover Card|Discover]] and Lego teamed up to make a new commercial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q8JPT5UjKJ4|title=\"Awesome\" Late Payment Forgiveness Discover it / The LEGO\u00ae Movie 2 Commercial :15|date=April 1, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ka6QuDtbr-A|title=\"Awesome\" Late Payment Forgiveness Discover it / The LEGO\u00ae Movie 2 Commercial :30|date=April 1, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2019}}</ref> Like the Chevy commercial, copyright infringements interfered with the video's official upload date on YouTube.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}} The commercial depicts two versions of Lucy, one running away from the Duplo Aliens, and the other in a damaged Lego architect of the Discover office building, who is fighting the stars from the Systar System.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{quotation|{{center|'''List indicator(s)'''}}}}\n* A dark grey cell indicates the character did not appear, or that the character's presence in the medium has not yet been announced.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Characters\n! colspan=\"4\" | Films\n! Attraction\n! Television series\n|-\n! style=\"width:12%\" | ''[[The Lego Movie]]''\n! style=\"width:15%\" | ''[[The Lego Batman Movie]]''\n! style=\"width:15%\" | ''[[The Lego Ninjago Movie]]''\n! style=\"width:12%\" | ''[[The Lego Movie 2: The Second Part]]''\n! style=\"width:12%\" | ''[[The Lego Movie: 4D \u2013 A New Adventure|{{small|The Lego Movie:}}<br>4D \u2013 A New Adventure]]''\n! style=\"width:12%\" | ''[[Unikitty!]]''\n|-\n! [[Emmet Brickowski|Emmet Brickowski<br>{{small|The Special}}]]\n| [[Chris Pratt]]\n| {{N/A|''Archive footage''}}\n| {{cEmpty}}\n| Chris Pratt\n| [[A. J. Locascio]]\n| {{cEmpty}}\n|-\n! [[List of The Lego Movie characters#Lucy \"Wyldstyle\"|Lucy \"Wyldstyle\"]]\n| [[Elizabeth Banks]]\n| colspan=\"2\" {{cEmpty}}\n| colspan=\"2\" | Elizabeth Banks\n| {{cEmpty}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Batman|Bruce Wayne<br>{{small|Batman}}]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Will Arnett]]\n| Will Arnett\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{cEmpty}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Will Arnett\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{cEmpty}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Will Arnett\n|-\n| {{N/A|[[Adam West]]<br>{{small|(''archive footage'')}}}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[List of The Lego Movie characters#Princess Unikitty|Princess Unikitty]]\n| rowspan=\"2